# PittaPDFToolkit — Project Rules

## Stack
- Tauri v2 (Rust backend) + React 19 + TypeScript (strict) + Vite 7
- Tailwind CSS v4, Zustand + Zundo, pdf.js, pdf-lib
- @tauri-apps/plugin-store for persistence

---

## Coding Rules

### TypeScript
- Strict mode enforced — no `any`, no unsafe type assertions
- Prefer `type` for shapes, `interface` when extension is intended
- Export types explicitly with `export type { … }`

### React
- Functional components only — no class components
- Use hooks for all stateful logic
- Avoid prop drilling — use Zustand store or context if a value crosses more than two component levels
- Prefer composition over growing a single large component

### File & Feature Structure
- Each feature lives under `src/features/<feature-name>/`
- Shared UI primitives → `src/components/ui/`
- Cross-feature utilities → `src/lib/`
- Global state → `src/store/`

### Documentation
- Every exported function MUST have a JSDoc comment (what it does, params, return, throws)
- No commented-out dead code — delete it, Git preserves history
- Keep comments current — stale comments are worse than none

### Size Limits
- Component files: ≤ 250 lines
- Function bodies: ≤ 40 lines when possible
- When a limit is reached, extract sub-components or custom hooks

### Constants
- No magic numbers — every non-obvious literal must be a named constant
- Use SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE for constants

### Logic
- No duplicated business logic — extract shared logic to `src/lib/`
- Keep business logic out of components; put it in hooks or lib functions

### Async & Errors
- Use async/await — avoid raw .then() chains
- Handle every possible error with try/catch
- Never silently swallow exceptions — at minimum log them, ideally surface to UI
- Never block the UI thread — all I/O and heavy computation must be async

### Testability
- Keep Tauri `invoke` and file I/O behind thin wrappers in `src/lib/tauri/` so they can be mocked
- Pure transformation functions must have zero dependency on Tauri APIs

### Naming
- Descriptive names that explain *what*, not *how*
- Files: `camelCase.ts` for utilities, `PascalCase.tsx` for components
- Constants: `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE`
- Types/Interfaces: `PascalCase`
- Hooks: `useDescriptiveName`

### Dependencies
- No unnecessary packages — justify every new dependency before adding it

---

## UI Design Rules

### Philosophy
Productivity tool, not a showcase. Make the user faster. When in doubt, do less.

### Style
- Minimal — show only what is needed for the current task
- Clean — generous whitespace, clear hierarchy, no visual noise
- Flat — flat shapes, single-colour fills, no skeuomorphism
- Native feeling — match desktop OS conventions

### Hard Avoids
- NO glassmorphism — no `backdrop-blur` on interactive surfaces
- NO fancy animations — no bounces, springs, or attention-seeking transitions
- NO gradient overload — gradients only as subtle page backgrounds
- NO heavy shadows — `shadow-sm` at most

### Layout
- Toolbar: frequently used actions only — secondary actions go in context menus
- Everything reachable within two clicks from the main view
- Never hide critical functionality behind hover-only states

### Motion
- All transitions ≤ 150ms
- Only use `transition-colors` and `transition-opacity` for micro-feedback
- Never animate layout shifts (height, width, position changes on lists)
- Instant state changes for explicit user actions (clicks, shortcuts)

### Colour & Theme
- Support light mode, dark mode, and system preference
- Use CSS custom properties from the token layer — never hardcode hex values
- All colour pairs must meet WCAG AA contrast (4.5:1 text, 3:1 UI)

### Display
- Support High DPI / Retina (2×) — SVG icons only, never fixed-size raster
- Layout must hold at 125%, 150%, 200% OS display scaling
- Test at minimum window size (800×600) and maximised

